text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Discrimination Against Mandarin Speakers%0a%0a:Author: khushiw%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn Hong Kong, where Cantonese is primarily spoken, individuals would discriminate against "outsiders" who spoke Mandarin.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/how-language-differences-can-spark-fear-racism-amid-the-coronavirus-pandemic%0a%0aAt the beginning of the pandemic, there was a lot of violence and discrimination in America, and obroad, against individuals of Asian descent. Even now, this violence has continued and Asian/Asian-American individuals are prejudiced against in society. One issue that has been greatly overlooked is internal language discrimination. In Hong Kong, 90%25 of the population speaks Cantonese. Although Mandarin is the official language of China, it is perceived as an “outsider’s tongue”. Hong Kong natives would recognize the difference between the two dialects (Mandarin has 4 tonal sounds instead of the 6 in Cantonese, Mandarin has simpler characters whereas Cantonese has the complex traditional ones, etc.) and discriminate against those that spoke a different dialect. These individuals were kicked out of restaurants and other public spaces. Though it is not as common today, individuals in the city would discriminate against those outside the city by recognizing the subtle differences between Mandarin and Cantonese as outlined above.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210424-210948-512320#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Extent of internal discrimination %0a-> - saraht%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI think Hong Kong-ers carry their discrimination over to the U.S., and apply it to any non-native accents when speaking Cantonese. My mom doesn't have an accent in English, but she also doesn't have an accent in Cantonese. This is surprising to a lot of Hong Kong natives because they hear her English and assume that she doesn't speak Mandarin or Cantonese. They'll find out she speaks Cantonese and then try to test it. They'll switch to Cantonese in the middle of their conversations, realize she has a native accent, and then become much friendlier towards her (not that they were hostile to her before, there was just a noticeable difference during/after their conversations).%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-210948-512320#%0a#foxbegin 210426-060820-659620#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Some personal experience %0a-> - xiranw%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThis is certainly not pleasant to talk about, but I can attest to this as it happened to my family when we visited Hong Kong almost 10 years ago. I only vaguely remember the visit (and I’m almost glad I don’t remember much, as it would likely just make me more outraged), but my parents say that we were ignored a few times when requesting service (checking in at a hotel, ordering at a restaurant, etc.) in Mandarin. Only after my parents switched to using English did we finally get serviced. %0a%0aI also remember one time in high school when I was talking to a friend who had just returned from a visit to Hong Kong to see family. She said that her family would always use Cantonese or English in public places because Mandarin speakers tended to be refused service. This discussion was actually what prompted me to ask my parents about our visit to Hong Kong, and I discovered that unfortunately, what my friend said was true.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210426-060820-659620#%0a#foxbegin 210504-131355-333230#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Experience of Cantonese vs Mandarin from personal experiences %0a-> - Spencer_L%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aHaving been raised by a parent, whose mother tongue is Cantonese, and another parent, whose mother tongue is Mandarin, I have noticed that there is also discrimination against Cantonese internally and externally. Even though I was exposed to both languages, I am only fluent in Mandarin and can only understand Cantonese to a certain extent. This is mainly due to the fact that my parents prioritized my education my Mandarin over Cantonese, due to the common usage of Mandarin in China. As I have seen from others of Chinese nationality, Cantonese is often noted by them to be loud and exaggerated. This brought me to question such logic, as I was curious how exactly this ideology was created. On main thing that I noticed (note that this may not be true as I am not a fluent Cantonese speaker) is that the extra two tones in Cantonese causes common day expressions to sound very exaggerated. To an extent, such extraneous tones may also have a correlation to being louder. In addition, I have also noticed many ideas that Cantonese is an ugly sounding language in comparison to Mandarin. I would like to note that these are just observations I have heard from others and I do not commit to these statements as facts. If my expansion is ignorant, please let me know and I will revise accordingly.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210504-131355-333230#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
time=1620134035
author:1620134035=Spencer_L
diff:1620134035:1619417297:=68,76d67%0a%3c #foxbegin 210504-131355-333230#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Experience of Cantonese vs Mandarin from personal experiences %0a%3c -> - Spencer_L%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Having been raised by a parent, whose mother tongue is Cantonese, and another parent, whose mother tongue is Mandarin, I have noticed that there is also discrimination against Cantonese internally and externally. Even though I was exposed to both languages, I am only fluent in Mandarin and can only understand Cantonese to a certain extent. This is mainly due to the fact that my parents prioritized my education my Mandarin over Cantonese, due to the common usage of Mandarin in China. As I have seen from others of Chinese nationality, Cantonese is often noted by them to be loud and exaggerated. This brought me to question such logic, as I was curious how exactly this ideology was created. On main thing that I noticed (note that this may not be true as I am not a fluent Cantonese speaker) is that the extra two tones in Cantonese causes common day expressions to sound very exaggerated. To an extent, such extraneous tones may also have a correlation to being louder. In addition, I have also noticed many ideas that Cantonese is an ugly sounding language in comparison to Mandarin. I would like to note that these are just observations I have heard from others and I do not commit to these statements as facts. If my expansion is ignorant, please let me know and I will revise accordingly.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210504-131355-333230#%0a
